24 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
SB1379 HFLR Page 1
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

CORRECTED
1 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 18r-1 of Title 74, unless there
3 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. For the purposes of this act:
5 1. “Labor trafficking” means human trafficking for labor as
6 defined in Section 748 of Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
7 2. “Private organization” means a nonprofit corporation
8 certified by the Office of the Attorney General that provides
9 support services to adult victims of human trafficking;
10 3. “Sexual trafficking” means human trafficking for commercial
11 sex as defined in Section 748 of Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
12 and
13 4. “Victim” means a person against whom an act of labor
14 trafficking or sexual trafficking has been committed.
15 B. 1. The Office of the Attorney General shall establish a
16 two-year pilot program to support victims of sexual and labor
17 trafficking. The Office of the Attorney General shall make grants
18 available from funds in the Victims of Human Trafficking and
19 Prevention Revolving Fund pursuant to Section 748.3 of Title 21 of
20 the Oklahoma Statutes for the purposes of this act. The grants
21 shall be made directly to no more than ten private organizations in
22 this state.
23 2. The purpose of such grants shall be to reimburse private
24 organizations for the qualifying expenses of programs providing
SB1379 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

CORRECTED
1 serv ices to victims of sexual and labor trafficking. Qualifying
2 expenses include, but are not limited to:
3 a. emergency shelter and transitional housing services,
4 b. mental health counseling and trauma-informed therapy,
5 c. medical and dental care services,
6 d. substance abuse treatment and recovery support,
7 e. legal assistance and advocacy services,
8 f. job training and employment assistance,
9 g. educational services and General Educational
10 Development (GED) completion assistance,
11 h. case management and coordination of services,
12 i. transportation assistance,
13 j. basic needs assistance including food, clothing, and
14 personal care items,
15 k. life skills training and financial literacy education,
16 l. child care services for victims with minor children,
17 and
18 m. other services deemed necessary by the Office of the
19 Attorney General for the recovery and restoration of
20 victims.
21 3. In order for a private organization to be considered
22 eligible to receive grants pursuant to the provisions of this
23 subsection, a private organization shall:
24
SB1379 HFLR Page 3
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

CORRECTED
1 a. be in good standing and compliant with nonprofit
2 requirements of this state and federal law,
3 b. have demonstrated experience providing services to
4 victims of sexual or labor trafficking,
5 c. agree to provide services without regard to the
6 immigration status of the victim,
7 d. maintain confidentiality of victim information in
8 accordance with applicable state and federal law, and
9 e. maintain adequate liability insurance coverage as
10 determined by the Office of the Attorney General.
11 4. The Office of the Attorney General shall establish an
12 application process and review criteria for private organizations
13 seeking grants pursuant to the provisions of this subsection. The
14 Office of the Attorney General shall prioritize organizations that:
15 a. demonstrate a track record of successful service
16 delivery to victims,
17 b. employ trauma-informed care practices,
18 c. provide culturally competent services,
19 d. collaborate with law enforcement and other service
20 providers, and
21 e. serve geographic areas or populations with
22 demonstrated need.
23 5. Grants provided to private organizations pursuant to this
24 act shall be used solely for the provision of direct services to
SB1379 HFLR Page 4
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

CORRECTED
1 vict ims and shall not be used for administrative overhead that
2 exceeds fifteen percent (15%) of the total grant amount.
3 C. Any private organization that receives a grant pursuant to
4 the provisions of this act shall submit quarterly reports to the
5 Office of the Attorney General that include the following
6 information:
7 1. Number of victims served;
8 2. Types of services provided to victims;
9 3. Expenditure of grant funds; and
10 4. Outcomes achieved to the extent measurable.
11 D. The Office of the Attorney General shall monitor compliance
12 of private organizations that receive grants pursuant to this act.
13 The Office of the Attorney General may:
14 1. Require periodic reports on services provided and outcomes
15 achieved;
16 2. Conduct site visits and review of grant recipients;
17 3. Review financial records and documentation of expenditures;
18 4. Require corrective action plans for organizations that do
19 not meet grant eligibility requirements; and
20 5. Suspend or terminate grants to private organizations that
21 fail to comply with the terms and conditions of the grant or the
22 requirements established pursuant to this act.
23 E. The Office of the Attorney General shall compile an annual
24 report regarding the implementation of the pilot program established
SB1379 HFLR Page 5
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

CORRECTED
1 in t his act. The report shall be submitted electronically to the
2 Governor, the President Pro Tempore of the Senate, and the Speaker
3 of the House of Representatives by December 1 of each year. The
4 report shall include:
5 1. The number of organizations that receive grants;
6 2. The total amount of grant funds distributed;
7 3. An aggregate summary of services provided and victims
8 served;
9 4. An evaluation of the effectiveness of the pilot program; and
10 5. Recommendations for improvement of the pilot program.
11 F. The Office of the Attorney General shall promulgate rules to
12 effectuate the provisions of this act.
13 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY Section 1, Chapter 376, O.S.L.
14 2023 (21 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 748.3), is amended to read as
15 follows:
16 Section 748.3. A. There is hereby created in the State
17 Treasury a revolving fund for the Office of the Attorney General to
18 be designated the “Victims of Human Trafficking and Prevention
19 Revolving Fund”. The fund shall be a continuing fund, not subject
20 to fiscal year limitations, and shall consist of all monies received
21 from penalties imposed by the courts on convictions of human
22 trafficking violations and funds received from any other source,
23 including legislative appropriations. All monies accruing to the
24 credit of the fund are hereby appropriated and may be budgeted and
SB1379 HFLR Page 6
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

CORRECTED
1 expe nded by the Office of the Attorney General for the purposes
2 provided in subsection B of this section. Expenditures from the
3 fund shall be made upon warrants issued by the State Treasurer
4 against claims filed as prescribed by law with the Director of the
5 Office of Management and Enterprise Services for approval and
6 payment.
7 B. The purposes of the fund include, but are not limited to:
8 1. Educating the public about the recruitment, trafficking, and
9 exploitation of persons through human trafficking;
10 2. Assisting in the prevention of recruitment in schools of
11 minors for exploitation;
12 3. Establishing a survivors’ resource center to make
13 information available to survivors of human trafficking about
14 services and resources, including legal services, social services,
15 safe harbors, safe houses, and language services;
16 4. Assisting in the coordination between law enforcement
17 agencies and service providers; and
18 5. Providing information concerning a petition for expungement
19 of a criminal history record resulting from the arrest or filing of
20 charges for an offense committed or reported to have been committed
21 while the person was a victim of human trafficking; and
22 6. Providing grants to nonprofit organizations pursuant to
23 Section 1 of this act.
24 SECTION 3. This act shall become effective July 1, 2026.
